ar East Suite: Ad Lib on Nippon", "w": "41009"}, {"t": "The Symphonic Duke", "w": "108452"}, {"t": "Reflections in D", "w": "71531"}, {"t": "Fleurette Africaine", "w": "38283"}, {"t": "Solitude", "w": "115641"}, {"t": "Come Sunday", "w": "122119"}, {"t": "V.I.P.'s Boogie", "w": "109372"}, {"t": "Black, Brown and Beige: Come Sunday", "w": "93713"}, {"t": "Mood Indigo", "w": "113788"}, {"t": "I’m Beginning to See the Light", "w": "58612"}, {"t": "Sophisticated Lady", "w": "106898"}, {"t": "Second Sacred Concert: T.G.T.T. (Too Good to Title)", "w": "79126"}, {"t": "Zonky Blues", "w": "60367"}, {"t": "Prelude to a Kiss", "w": "100201"}, {"t": "New World A-Comin'", "w": "93357"}, {"t": "Ring Dem Bells", "w": "26167"}, {"t": "Reflections in D", "w": "117513"}, {"t": "Sono", "w": "51930"}, {"t": "I'm Just A Lucky So and So", "w": "37340"}, {"t": "Crescendo in Blue", "w": "521"}, {"t": "Second Sacred Concert: Almighty God", "w": "59274"}, {"t": "Rue Bleue", "w": "67254"}, {"t": "Love in My Heart (Swing Baby Swing)", "w": "56329"}, {"t": "Far East Suite: Agra", "w": "61212"}], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "Avakian George", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "I got into Ellington because of the popular songs that he wrote and recorded... I remember one of the first ones that I ever bought was Sophisticated Lady... I started going really to hear the Basie band... listening to Ellington and Basie, particularly... I was sitting opposite the Ellington band..", "doc_title": "Avakian George — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://americanhistory.si.edu/sites/default/files/file-uploader/Avakian-George-Transcription-2020.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Arnett Cobb", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "The transcript mentions 'Duke Garrett' and 'Duke Ellington' as separate entities. The interviewee (Arnett Cobb) discusses 'Duke Garrett' extensively (visiting him, him being a trumpet player, staying together with him). There is no mention of Duke Ellington in the interviewee's responses, only in th", "doc_title": "63475_Arnett Cobb oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/63475/"}, {"speaker": "Candido Camero", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Then we did the recording, too. In this recording was that song A Drum is a Woman... And after that, I also worked with his son, Mercer Ellington. I worked with his son also after Duke Ellington. That was the . . . how the relationship between Duke Ellington and me began.", "doc_title": "Candido Camero — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Camero-Candido/Camero_Candido_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Big Chielf Moore", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "The interviewee's name is Big Chief Moore. The transcript contains only the interviewer mentioning Duke Ellington and his band members. There is no statement from the interviewee indicating any personal interaction, collaboration, or relationship with Duke Ellington.", "doc_title": "67259_Big Chief Moore oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/67259/"}, {"speaker": "John Lamb", "relation": "played under", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Duke Ellington... says, 'well look here, Mr. Lamb, we’d like you to come up to New York and play some things with us.' ... 'are you here, the new bass player?' ... 'you want to take the next set?' ... 'Duke came in the next night and we began at Basin Street East'", "doc_title": "John Lamb interviewed by Monk Rowe, Clearwater Beach, Florida, March 16, 2001", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/john-lamb-interviewed-monk-rowe-clearwater-beach-florida-march-16-2001"}, {"speaker": "William Russell", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "The interviewee mentions Ellington only in the context of Barney Bigard's career ('he just played with Ellington because Ellington had hired him'), with no personal interaction or direct relationship described between William Russell and Duke Ellington.", "doc_title": "William Russell Interview, 1962-09-04", "collection": "tulane", "url": "https://library.search.tulane.edu/permalink/01TUL_INST/4h6sc4/alma9945592975606326"}]}